these real, by the way? I can’t tell if
they’re made out of foam or digital. So

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:14.440
what happened? TECHNOLOGY! Here’s my definition:

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:17.890
The Industrial Revolution was an increase
in production brought about by the use of

00:02:17.890 --> 00:02:22.400
machines and characterized by the use of new
energy sources. Although this will soon get

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:26.810
more complicated, for our purposes today,
industrialization is NOT capitalism - although,

00:02:26.810 --> 00:02:30.070
as we will see next week, it is connected
to modern capitalism. And, the industrial

00:02:30.070 --> 00:02:34.560
revolution began around 1750 and it occurred
across most of the earth, but it started in

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:38.220
Europe, especially Britain. What happened?
Well, let’s go to the Thought Bubble.

00:02:38.220 --> 00:02:41.700
The innovations of the Industrial Revolution
were intimately interconnected. Like, look,

00:02:41.700 --> 00:02:46.040
for instance, at the British textile industry:
The invention of the flying shuttle by John

00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:51.430
Kay in 1733 dramatically increased the speed
of weaving, which in turn created demand for

00:02:51.430 --> 00:02:56.650
yarn, which led to inventions like the Spinning
Jenny and the water frame. Soon these processes

00:02:56.650 --> 00:03:00.840
were mechanized using water power, until the
steam engine came along to make flying shuttles

00:03:00.840 --> 00:03:03.760
really fly in these huge cotton mills.

00:03:03.760 --> 00:03:07.480
The most successful steam engine was built
by Thomas “They Didn’t Name Anything After

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:12.110
Me” Newcomen to clear water out of mines.
And because water was cleared out of those

00:03:12.110 --> 00:03:16.040
mines, there was more coal to power more steam
engines, which eventually led to the fancying

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:20.290
up of the Newcomen Steam Engine by James “I
Got a Unit of Power and a University Named

00:03:20.290 --> 00:03:25.520
After Me” Watt, whose engine made possible
not only railroads and steamboats but also

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:27.570
ever-more-efficient cotton mills.

00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:31.920
And, for the first time, chemicals other than
stale urine (I wish I was kidding) were being

00:03:31.920 --> 00:03:36.880
used to bleach the cloth that people wore
- the first of which was sulfuric acid, which

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:41.430
was created in large quantities only thanks
to lead-lined chambers, which would’ve been

00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:46.770
impossible without lead production rising
dramatically right around 1750 in Britain,

00:03:46.770 --> 00:03:49.350
thanks to lead foundries powered by coal.

00:03:49.350 --> 00:03:53.270
And all these factors came together to make
more yarn that could be spun and bleached

00:03:53.270 --> 00:03:58.600
faster and cheaper than ever before, a process
that would eventually culminate in $18 Crash

